<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Detention Action (JRR 0013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Public interest litigation is a vital means for civil society to challenge breaches of human rights by government and public bodies.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposed changes would all but eliminate such litigation in the public interest.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This would reduce human rights litigation to individual cases, which themselves are under threat from th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e proposed changes to legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About Detention Action</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Detention Action (formerly London Detainee Support Group) is a national charity established in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1993 that aims to change the way that migrants are treated by immigration detention policy in the UK.  Detention Action defends the rights and improves the welfare of people in detention by combining support for individuals with campaigning for policy chan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ge.  Detention Action works primarily in Harmondsworth and Colnbrook Immigration Removal Centres, near Heathrow Airport in London.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Standing and third party interventions</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposals exclude from judicial review almost all public interest litigation, r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">egardless of the strength of the case, the gravity of the impact on human rights, and the public interest in it being heard.  This draconian step is justified with reference to assertions, unsupported by evidence, as to the motivations of some litigants.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Ministry of Justice, in the consultation document “Judicial review - proposals for further reform”, asserts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that claims are brought “sometimes for reasons only of publicity or to cause delay.”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  No evidence is produced that any judicial reviews are bro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ught for these reasons.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The courts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">already</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assess whether it is in the public interest for a case to be heard; a claim brought purely for reasons of publicity or delay would not meet this test and would not go forward.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as the consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">document </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acknowledges, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the relevant data shows that judicial reviews by claimants without a direct interest are “relatively successful compared to other JR cases”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a higher proportion of these cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being found</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to have merits by the courts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: 40% are gra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nted permission and 12% are successful.  Moreover, only 50 such judicial reviews are lodged per year, 0.4% of the total of judicial reviews.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The very small number of public interest judicial reviews will cost a tiny proportion of public spending on jud</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">icial reviews.  They are far more likely to succeed than other judicial reviews, and the wider benefits to society are likely to be larger, since by definition they address questions of the public interest. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The proposal to prevent them from being brought </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may be convenient to Government in protecting it from awkward challenges, yet it is profoundly harmful to democracy and an active civil society.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affected will be of the highest consequence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for the human rights of the people involved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  In most c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ases, the alleged breach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> simply cannot be challenged in the courts by individuals affected.  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">example given in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation document, the challenge by Maya Evans to the transfer of detainees of the UK armed forces to the Afghan authorities, is a cle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ar example of an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a major alleged</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">human rights abuse that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">victims are in no position to litigate.  Excluding such alleged abuses from judicial scrutiny would have a serious impact on human rights protection in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another example is the case of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Med</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ical Justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (201</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">),</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which involved a successful challenge to the Home Office’s unlawful practice of removing vulnerable people without giving them the normal period of notice.  The nature of the action at issue prevented the victims from accessing legal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">advice and challenging it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, since they would already have been unlawfully removed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Where such removal would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">expose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> them to breaches of their human rights, including absolute rights such as the Article 3 prohibition on torture or inhuman and degrading</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> treatment, they would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nevertheless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no means of defending their rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These examples are typical in that there is potential for serious breaches of human rights of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highly vulnerable people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with protected characteristics.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NGOs have an important role to play in monitoring the treatment of the most vulnerable people in society, given their access to disadvantaged individuals, specialist knowledge and ability to identify important issues of systemic abuse of human rights.  The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proposals would make many such actions by public authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> effectively immune from legal challenge and scrutiny.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Judicial reviews are a crucial safeguard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the human rights of vulnerable people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">against the unconstrained power of the state.  The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proposals will make judicial review work financially unviable in the majority of cases, as large amounts of work will be ‘at risk’.  Given the precarious financial situation of legal aid immigration firms even prior to these proposals, immigration judicia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l reviews will in general no longer be brought under legal aid.  As a result, people with strong cases will be unable to access justice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government has accepted that the original proposals would have targeted meritorious cases where permission is not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">granted because the case settles prior to reaching the court.  In response, it has introduced a concession whereby the Legal Aid Authority (LAA) would have discretion to pay providers in certain meritorious cases where the provider has been unable to secur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e a costs order as part of a settlement.  This concession fails adequately to address the disincentive created by the proposals to bring meritorious judicial reviews.  Pre-permission work on judicial reviews remains ‘at risk’.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposal relies on the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> false basis that “the legal representative is in the best position to advise their client of the likelihood of success”.  This is simply untrue; it is the defendant public authority that is in the best position to assess the merits of the vast majority of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> claims because it generally has access to all the relevant information about how the decision was reached.  Rules on disclosure mean that claimants will not have access to this information until the judicial review is already underway.  As a result, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">even </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strong judicial reviews </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on compelling human rights grounds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">correctly brought inevitably involve a risk of refusal of permission.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Given the narrow profit margins involved, solicitors will be unable to carry the risk of a significant proportion of their judicial review work going unpaid.  Given that they will be unable to accurately determine in advance which cases will not be paid, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he logical conclusion will be not to bring any of the cases.  Lawyers who continue to perform their professional duty to their clients, working to a high standard, will frequently go unpaid.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">More likely, vulnerable people experiencing abuse of their human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rights will be unable to access justice because solicitors will be unable to establish with sufficient </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certainty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> before bringing the judicial review that the case will be successful.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The criteria by which LAA are to assess whether to make a discretionary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> payment are narrow, and clearly drafted so as to minimise the number of such payments.  The inadequacy of a safeguard based on LAA discretion is highlighted by the assurances given during the passage of LASPO that LAA would grant exceptional funding where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> necessary in Article 8 cases.    Research shows that by July 2013 only 233 applications had been received, compared to an expected 5,000 to 7,000 applications, by July 2013 only 233 had been received, and only six had been granted.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Moreover, the substan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tial numbers of cases in which the defendant settles before the judicial review is issued would not be eligible for discretionary payments for the, often substantial, work done.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Taken in conjunction with the proposals on standing, this would appear to eli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">minate all public interest litigation: cases without a direct interest would be excluded from judicial review altogether, whereas cases where there is a direct interest would not be eligible for PCOs.  PCOs are granted to allow small organisations to litig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ate in the public interest, where they would otherwise be prevented from doing so by the risks of a costs order.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without the availability of PCOs, these cases by definition would not be brought.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These proposals would make it effectively impossible for al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">l but the largest and best funded civil society organisations to bring litigation in the public interest.  Access to the courts would be limited according to ability to pay the legal costs of Government departments that frequently spend large sums instruct</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing leading barristers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The impact of these proposals on human rights protection will be exacerbated by the current proposals on legal aid, which would exclude migrants not lawfully resident in the UK.  The government proposes simultaneously to exclude in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dividuals from the legal aid that they need to challenge abuse, and to prevent organisations from challenging such abuse at a systemic level.  This amounts to a two-pronged assault on the ability of the justice system to defend the human rights of migrants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Ministry of Justice, “Judicial review - proposals for further reform,” 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">p22, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">4.67</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Ibid, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">p 24, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">4.78</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> R (Medical Justice) vs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Secretary of State for the Home Department, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">[2010] EWHC 1925 (Admin)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Martha Spurrier, Public Law Project, see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://legalaidchanges.wordpress.com/2013/07/08/martha-spurrier-exceptional-funding-does-notprotect-access-to-justice/.</span></p></body></html>